r a meadow, from Middle High German <i>matte</i> ‘meadow’.","German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> or <i>Matthäus</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Matter","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone who lived by a meadow, from   Matte   1 + <i>-er</i>, suffix denoting an inhabitant.","English (Lancashire); Dutch (also <b>De Matter</b>): occupational name for a maker of mats, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>matte</i>, Middle Dutch <i>mat</i> ‘mat’."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]}]},{"name":"Conduit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Middle English  <i>conduit</i>,  <i>condit</i>,  <i>cundit</i>, originally an artificial channel or pipe for conveying water, later a fountain or pump. The surname probably refers to the latter.  <i>Condict</i> and  <i>Cundict</i> are hypercorrect pronunciations of  <i>Condit</i> and  <i>Cundit</i>, subsequently altered to  <i>Conduct</i> by folk etymology. The surname may sometimes have been confused with   Cundy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Condict","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brigid, Fergus, Liam.","English (Cornwall): hypercorrected form of <b>Condit(t)</b> and <b>Cundit(t)</b>, from Middle English <i>conduit, condit, cundit</i>, originally an artificial channel or pipe for conveying water, later a fountain or pump (the surname probably refers to the latter). The surname may sometimes have been confused with   Cundy  . See also   Condit  .","Irish: variant of   Connick  , a patronymic from Gaelic <b>Mac Conmhaic</b>."]},{"name":"Condick","meanings":["English:  see  Conduit   and  compare  Conduct  ."]},{"name":"Cundict","meanings":["English:  see  Conduit   and  compare  Conduct  ."]},{"name":"Cundy","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy and Picardy called Condé, a French form of the Gaulish <i>condate</i> ‘junction of rivers’. Members of the de Condé family held land in Lincolnshire, Kent, Leicestershire, Cambridgeshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th century. The strong presence of the surname in 16th-century Cornwall and Devon is unexpected, but is probably the result of migration from counties further east or north. Derivation from the Cornish language is implausible, and there is no known place in Cornwall which could have given rise to it as a habitational name."]},{"name":"Cundick","meanings":["English:  see  Conduit   and  compare  Conduct  ."]},{"nam